00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:21.933
My name is Lucerito Ortiz.
I’m from North Hills, California.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.100
My parents are
two of the hardest-working people.

00:05:24.167 --> 00:05:26.600
My dad works in gardening.

00:05:26.667 --> 00:05:29.367
My mom found work as a housekeeper.

00:05:29.433 --> 00:05:31.633
We have a big family.

00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:35.767
We have to find ways to save
as much as we can.

00:05:35.833 --> 00:05:38.200
I learned to sew.

00:05:38.267 --> 00:05:42.433
We have chickens, so that way
we don’t have to buy eggs.

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:45.567
They’re very, very delicious.
Much better than store-bought eggs.

00:05:45.633 --> 00:05:50.200
And we cook at home.
It’s different ways to save money.

00:05:50.267 --> 00:05:53.000
They’ll sacrifice anything and everything
for their children...

00:05:53.067 --> 00:05:56.867
and they’ve worked incredibly hard
to get us to where we are.

00:05:56.933 --> 00:06:01.733
My daughter is a very, very
responsible person...

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:03.833
and she loved school.

00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:07.833
But I ended up applying
sort of as a joke, as a dare.

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:13.800
A couple of friends and I were
out on the track one day, just chatting.

00:06:13.867 --> 00:06:16.467
We just said–
We were laughing–

00:06:16.533 --> 00:06:18.933
“It would be so funny
if you applied to Harvard.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.500
We could frame your rejection letter.”

00:06:20.567 --> 00:06:22.467
One day, Lucerito called me...

00:06:22.533 --> 00:06:25.933
and she said,
“Mom, guess what.”

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.100
The letter was there.
I was on the phone with my mom.

00:06:28.167 --> 00:06:29.667
I said, “Mom, hold on.”

00:06:29.733 --> 00:06:34.567
And then she said,
“Mom, I was accepted at Harvard.”

00:06:34.633 --> 00:06:37.300
I ran all over my house,
just yelling and screaming...

00:06:37.367 --> 00:06:38.967
and told my whole family...

00:06:39.033 --> 00:06:41.167
and we were all just in utter shock.

00:06:41.233 --> 00:06:45.233
My husband and I talked about,
“We don’t have the money.”

00:06:45.300 --> 00:06:48.167
I found out that for a family like ours...

00:06:48.233 --> 00:06:51.267
we wouldn’t have to worry
about affording Harvard.

00:06:51.333 --> 00:06:54.100
Harvard has such an amazing
financial aid program...

00:06:54.167 --> 00:06:57.833
that for us, in reality,
it was much more affordable...

00:06:57.900 --> 00:07:00.567
than attending any of the state schools.

00:07:00.633 --> 00:07:04.900
I really, really admire her,
and I’m so proud of her.

00:07:04.967 --> 00:07:08.133
For me, Harvard wasn’t just for me...

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:09.900
it was for my whole family...

00:07:09.967 --> 00:07:14.200
and I think my whole family
has benefited immensely...

00:07:14.267 --> 00:07:16.767
from our experience at Harvard.

00:07:16.833 --> 00:07:20.300
It’s an incredible feeling...

00:07:20.367 --> 00:07:24.367
to feel like I was finally able
to give something back to my family...

00:07:24.433 --> 00:07:27.833
after everything they sacrificed for me.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.167
One of the most important aspects
of teaching the humanities...

00:07:37.233 --> 00:07:40.567
is to transmit cultural values across time.

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:48.900
We pursue the study with the conviction
that we’re training global citizens.

00:07:48.967 --> 00:07:55.200
Expanding your horizons
and learning how to ask new questions...

00:07:55.267 --> 00:07:58.267
and learning how to have
your questions answered.

00:08:00.067 --> 00:08:04.567
This is a place that has art museums
that are unique...

00:08:04.633 --> 00:08:07.000
in their depth and their breadth.

00:08:07.067 --> 00:08:12.867
The humanities shift and change
as the great public issues...

00:08:12.933 --> 00:08:15.500
and public questions of our times change.

00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:21.333
By the time you graduate and you’ve picked
a concentration or a major...

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:26.433
you’re really poised to do many
and often unpredictable things.

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:31.400
Harvard is, in the best sense,
a global university.

00:08:38.167 --> 00:08:40.200
[ Emerance Narrating ] You can look
just about anywhere from my house...

00:08:40.267 --> 00:08:43.767
and you would see strictly land,
and that’s about it.

00:08:43.833 --> 00:08:45.500
I live in Alberta, Canada.

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:49.733
My great-great-grandparents
came over here over a century ago...

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:52.900
and started a farm, and my dad
still farms the same farm today.

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:57.533
In Canada, there’s only two seasons.
One season is farming season.

00:09:01.033 --> 00:09:02.600
The other is hockey season.

00:09:03.600 --> 00:09:05.867
I have a brother, Bronson.
My sister is Brittaney.

00:09:05.933 --> 00:09:08.767
I have a brother, Brock,
and a younger brother, Kache.

00:09:09.433 --> 00:09:10.600
We all play hockey.

00:09:10.667 --> 00:09:15.167
Since I was little, there was just one team.
I played with the guys.

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:18.000
After that, I continued playing guys’ hockey.

00:09:18.067 --> 00:09:19.867
I wanted to challenge myself all the time...

00:09:19.933 --> 00:09:23.133
and prove to everyone that I could be
just as good as the guys.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:25.667
When I was 13 years old,
the team that I was playing on...

00:09:25.733 --> 00:09:27.367
went to Boston for a tournament.

00:09:27.433 --> 00:09:31.633
My mom and I went together,
and we toured Harvard.

00:09:31.700 --> 00:09:33.700
I fell in love with it right away.

00:09:33.767 --> 00:09:36.167
I told my mom,
“I’m gonna go here one day.”

00:09:36.233 --> 00:09:38.833
My mom and dad taught us kids
to work really hard...

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:40.833
and always challenge ourselves.

00:09:40.900 --> 00:09:43.333
They told us to have a good work ethic,
and no matter what...

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:46.033
no matter how hard it was,
to stick with it and you’ll get through it...

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:47.567
and eventually, you’ll have success.

00:09:48.300 --> 00:09:50.633
My name is Emerance Maschmeyer...

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:53.200
and I play goalie
for the Harvard women’s ice hockey team.

00:09:58.167 --> 00:10:01.167
[ Nicholas Narrating ]
I’m a journalist and Harvard class of 1982.

00:10:01.233 --> 00:10:03.200
I’ve lived all over:

00:10:03.933 --> 00:10:05.833
Egypt and Oxford.

00:10:06.367 --> 00:10:08.200
China and Congo.

00:10:08.267 --> 00:10:12.333
And in my travels, I’ve discovered
that Harvard isn’t just a place...

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:14.400
it’s a community.

00:10:14.967 --> 00:10:17.933
I found support through Harvard bonds.

00:10:18.700 --> 00:10:23.833
There are more than 350,000 alumni
scattered all over the world.

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:25.700
We’re waiting for you to join us.

00:10:26.467 --> 00:10:28.433
My name is Nicholas Kristof.

00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:33.067
When you consider Harvard,
make sure to consider...

00:10:34.267 --> 00:10:35.833
what comes after.

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:42.300
[ Male Student Narrating ]
My professor is the president...

00:10:42.367 --> 00:10:45.067
of the Society for the Study of Evolution...

00:10:45.133 --> 00:10:47.167
and the American Genetic Association.

00:10:48.933 --> 00:10:53.933
He’s respected for employing genetic tools
for the study of evolutionary biology.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:11:00.367
He believes that close social bonds help
the group to work better together in the lab.

00:11:01.333 --> 00:11:06.267
We work side-by-side to analyze the data
from my field research in Australia...

00:11:07.267 --> 00:11:10.233
and to study the evolution of a pathogen.

00:11:11.767 --> 00:11:15.500
We’re doing the kind of science
that the world expects from Harvard.

00:11:16.767 --> 00:11:19.867
I just never expected to do it
over breakfast.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:28.700
The first line of my application here...

00:11:28.767 --> 00:11:32.333
said, “For as long as I can remember,
I’ve wanted to be an actor.”

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.400
It was asking kind of who you were,
and that was really who I was...

00:11:35.467 --> 00:11:37.133
and I wanted them to know who I was...

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:39.333
and, whether they accepted me or not...

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:41.667
I wanted them to know
who they were gonna let in or not.

00:11:41.733 --> 00:11:45.933
Having grown up here, I think I had one way
of looking at Harvard–

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.233
kind of a townie view of the school.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:50.933
Suddenly walking through
as a prospective student...

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.767
I just started to really take in
how impressive it was.

00:11:53.833 --> 00:11:56.600
I assumed if I could get
into an Ivy League school–

00:11:56.667 --> 00:11:59.033
That kind of touched every base for me.

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:03.600
And then I got into Harvard,
and it’s a very tough place to turn down.

00:12:03.667 --> 00:12:07.600
This great teacher named Anthony Kubiak–
I took a number of his classes.

00:12:07.667 --> 00:12:10.167
This was the final one that I took.
It was the playwriting class.

00:12:10.233 --> 00:12:12.867
I handed in the first act
of a three-act movie–

00:12:12.933 --> 00:12:14.433
what eventually became
Good Will Hunting.

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:18.000
I apologized to him when I handed him
this 40-some-odd page document.

00:12:18.067 --> 00:12:20.667
I just said,
“I don’t think I did what you wanted.

00:12:20.733 --> 00:12:22.300
I was supposed to write a one-act play...

00:12:22.367 --> 00:12:25.900
and this is clearly the first act
of a three-act movie.”

00:12:25.967 --> 00:12:28.033
He was unbelievably encouraging.

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:31.267
He gave me a flat “A” in the class,
which was a big deal.

00:12:31.333 --> 00:12:34.667
He wrote extensively in the margins–

00:12:34.733 --> 00:12:37.467
or on a cover page that he put on it–

00:12:37.533 --> 00:12:40.367
to “please keep up with this”–

00:12:40.433 --> 00:12:43.100
that it was worthy,
that it was good...

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:46.600
that it wasn’t anything
close to a failure...

00:12:46.667 --> 00:12:48.200
that it was something I had to pursue.

00:12:48.267 --> 00:12:50.967
So I showed it to Ben Affleck,
and the rest is history.

